The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Monday, July 19, 2004  The City Diary
																																																		The Regional Transport Authority and the West Bengal Contract Carriage Owners and Operators Association have jointly decided to make it mandatory for schoolbuses to display a board indicating that the vehicles are on school duty. A high-level meeting was held on Friday, in which nine other guidelines were framed for the schoolbus operators. Association secretary Himadri Ganguly said his organisation would not take responsibility for buses that fail to comply with the guidelines, including painting the buses yellow and blue, within August 15.																																																		Acting on a tip-off, a special team of police arrested four persons from different parts of Howrah town on Saturday in connection with hijacking of oil tankers on the highways. According to the officers, the miscreants, operating for over two years now, would waylay the tankers in the guise of policemen and sell the stolen oil at a premium.																																																		The body of Dola Mondal, 20, was fished out from Baniban canal on Saturday night in Howrahs Uluberia by divers deployed by the police. Mondal went for a bath in the evening but didnt return, police said. The body was sent for post-mortem. 																																																		Five persons were arrested and 11 firearms were seized from them at Banipur, in the Barasat area, on Saturday evening. Fifty three rounds of .303 cartridges, 12 bombs, two motorcycles and two mobile phones were also recovered. Interrogation revealed the contract killers were involved in around 15 murders. The killers would either leave the bodies on rail tracks or dump them in a canal.To Uttar Shikha for organising a cultural programme to raise funds for the spastic children of Missionaries of Charity
